oudest aircraft ever flown.<ref># Knaack, Marcelle Size. Encyclopedia of U.S. Air Force Aircraft and Missile Systems: Volume 1 Post-World War II Fighters 1945\u20131973. Washington, D.C.: Office of Air Force History, 1978. {{ISBN|0-912799-59-5}}.</ref>  The Thunderscreech, however, was a much later design, being a contemporary of the clearly second generation [[F-104 Starfighter]].  None of these hybrid-propulsion planes saw combat or major use, though the Fireball was used operationally for two years.\n\n== Post-World War II ==\n[[Image:MiG-15 RB1.jpg|thumb|right|A MiG-15 in [[Poland|Polish]] markings]]\n\nAfter World War II, some additional aircraft were built using refinements of the ideas used in the first attempts.  Some of these included a [[swept wing]] and some could break the [[sound barrier]] in a dive, but almost all of them lacked the [[thrust]] to do so in level flight.  [[Radar]] was used in dedicated [[interceptor aircraft|interceptors]] and [[night fighters]] but early models required a dedicated radar operator.  These aircraft are mostly associated with the [[Korean War]].  Some [[interceptor aircraft|interceptor]] designs, such as the [[F-94 Starfire|F-94]] used rockets such as the [[Mk 4/Mk 40 Folding-Fin Aerial Rocket]] as their primary weapon instead of guns.\n\n===Interceptors/Night fighters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! Aircraft\n! Primary<br/>Builder \n! Number<br/>built\n! First<br/>flight\n! Service<br/>life\n! Length<br/>m\n! Wingspan<br/>m\n! Wing area<br/>sq. m\n! Empty<br/>weight\n! Max takeoff<br/>weight\n! Max Speed<br>km/h\n! Range<br>km\n! Ceiling<br>m\n! Engines<br>\u00d7<br>Thrust\n|-\n| [[Avro CF-100]] || {{flag|Canada|1921}} || 692 || 1950 || 1952-1981 ||  16.50 || 17.40 || 54.9 || 10,500&nbsp;kg|| 16,329&nbsp;kg || 888 || 3,200 || 13,700 || 2 \u00d7 32.5&nbsp;kN\n|-\n| [[de Havilland Venom|DH 112 Venom]] || {{flag|United Kingdom|UK}} || 1,431 || 1949 || 1952-1983 ||  9.70 || 12.70 || 25.